<b>Use a text macro to help out - </b>7/13/01 4:38:15 PM<br>~ <b>Arathros</b><blockquote>You can really help out with crowd control if you add a couple of text macros to your hot key boxes.  One that I use with Pixie Strike is a macro that basically says:<br><br>I am MESSING the %T, please don't wake it up!<br><br>Hit this button before or after you use the song on your target (by the %T) and it raises the chances your group will leave it alone.  I have a similar text macro for my charm hot key box group.</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b> - </b>5/3/01 2:36:02 AM<br>~ <b>skulrag</b><blockquote>I love this song on hate raids, those dumb Clerics of inny always CH and i just chain mez um :) record is 5 inturrutps w/one cleric of inny =) also good for rogue/bard group, you chain mez, they chain backstab :p</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Some tips for using this song. - </b>4/16/01 1:49:15 PM<br>~ <b>Belark Songstrider</b><blockquote>This is an excellent song, and one that you will really begin to use a lot once you get into dungeon settings. <br><br>A few tips- If there is a capable enchanter in your group, let them handle messing. For some reason, your mes overwrites theirs, and doesn’t last nearly as long.<br><br>If there is not an enchanter, it's up to you to be crowd control for the group. Get out your wind instrument - it doesn’t make it more likely to succeed, but it lowers magic resistance by a greater amount when it does succeed, making it easier to re-mes. <br><br>Realistically, you cannot keep more than two things messed at once. Resists and the difficulties of retargeting make it really tough. Make sure your group knows this, and has a plan to deal with more than 3 things. <br><br>Group coordination is critical - It is VITAL that your group assists the lead, so that people aren't bashing your messed target. If you have a shaman who can slow, make sure they know that slowing your messed targets will really help you keep them messed. (They usually don't know this.)<br><br>Other uses of this song:<br><br>As mentioned, this song will interrupt a spell caster if he is still in his 'windup', and the song is not resisted. GREAT song for preventing healers from healing. <br><br>The other use of this song is the knock back effect. In testing, this song actually pushes the target a little bit in the DIRECTION YOU ARE FACING WHEN THE SONG TAKES EFFECT. So you can actually &quot;steer&quot; the target by singing this song. Need to pull him towards you? Target him, turn around so he's behind ya, and sing away. Bump him to the left? Target, turn left, and sing away. Can be useful for nudging things off of ledges or keeping them in a certain spot. <br><br>-Belark Songstrider, 51st Minstrel of Drinal<br><br><br> </blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Mezz - </b>3/14/01 12:08:43 AM<br>~ <b>Kocho Divah</b><blockquote>I always have this song memmed now. It acts as a Mezz, so if you get multiple pulls, you can mezz one for a good chunk of the time while you're fighting the first one. I love acting as crowd control with this song and Charm songs!</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Usefulness is against casters - </b>1/29/01 6:08:20 PM<br>~ <b>Quelionis</b><blockquote>This song is to be used against all caster types, when it hits it will disrupt the casters concentration 99% of the time, very good against any casters who heal themselves or others. I cast this song repeatedly while the group maims the mob. A top notch song to have in a casting situation.</blockquote></td></tr><tr bgcolor="#eeeeee"><td>
<b>Interrupting Casters! - </b>1/29/01 5:31:35 PM<br>~ <b>Kocho Divah</b><blockquote>If you're up against any kind of caster, mem this song. If you see them starting to cast a spell, hit this song, and you'll likely interrupt them. If not provoked, the mob will stand there stunned for up to 18 seconds. So when fighting a caster, don't be afraid to chain sing this song. It also adds a nice MR debuff.</blockquote></td></tr></table></blockquote><br><br><br><br><br><br><a href="/songs.asp?&song=29">Back to Normal Mode</a><br><br><br><i>Printed from EQDiva.com on 7/24/01 12:27:32 PM.</i><br><br></td></tr></table>
